from a standard deck, the probability that both the first and second are aces \
is ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["4", "52"], "\[CenterDot]", 
    FractionBox["3", "51"]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", that is, the probability that the first is an ace times the conditional \
probability that the second is an ace given that the first is an ace.  For \
three aces in a row, the probability would become ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{
    FractionBox["4", "52"], "\[CenterDot]", 
    FractionBox["3", "51"], "\[CenterDot]", 
    FractionBox["2", "50"]}], TraditionalForm]]],
 ", in which the third factor is the conditional probability that the third \
card is an ace given that both of the first two cards are aces. \n\tThe \
example of the three aces suggests that formula (2) can be generalized as in \
the following theorem.  You are asked to prove it in Exercise 7.  Notice that \
from stage to stage one must condition not only on the immediately preceding \
event but all past events."
}], "Text",
