Cell[TextData[{
 StyleBox["Example 2",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "  Exercise 5 in Section 1.4 described the following famous problem.  \
Suppose you ask a room of ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " people for their birthdays, one by one.  What is the probability that \
there will be at least one set of matching birthdays?\n\tIn the exercise you \
were expected to use combinatorics to solve the problem.  Here we take a \
conditional probability approach using formula (3).  It is convenient to \
study the complementary event of no matching birthdays.  Let ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["B", "1"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " be the event that there is no match after the first person is asked, which \
has probability 1. Let ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["B", "2"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " be the event that there is no match after the first two people, which has \
conditional probability 364/365 given ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["B", "1"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " since one birthday is disallowed.  Similarly, if ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["B", "3"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " is the event that there is no match after the first three people, then ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["B", "3"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " has conditional probability 363/365 given the event ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["B", "1"], TraditionalForm]]],
 "\[Intersection]",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["B", "2"], TraditionalForm]]],
 " of no previous matches.  For ",
 StyleBox["n",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " people we have"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.423913230296875*^9, 3.42391323121875*^9}, {
  3.42392742771875*^9, 3.423927432109375*^9}}],

