Cell[TextData[{
 "The results are very striking for a small ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " value of .001, and would be more so for even smaller ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "'s: increasing ",
 StyleBox["q",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " toward 1 produces only roughly linear increases in our objective ",
 StyleBox["f",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", to a level even less than .1.  In other words, even if the test was made \
extremely accurate on persons with HIV, it is still unlikely that someone \
with a positive HIV screening actually is infected.  This may be due to the \
very small ",
 StyleBox["p",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " in the numerator, which is overcome by the term ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   RowBox[{"r", "(", 
    RowBox[{"1", "-", "p"}], ")"}], TraditionalForm]]],
 " in the denominator. By contrast, the rate of increase of ",
 StyleBox["f",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " as ",
 StyleBox["r",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " decreases toward 0 is much more rapid, at least once the screening reaches \
an error rate of less than .05.  When the probability of an incorrect \
positive test on a person without HIV is sufficiently reduced, the \
probability that truly HIV is present when the screening test reads positive \
dramatically increases toward 1. A 3D plot shows this effectively.  (The code \
to produce it is in the closed cell above ",
 StyleBox["Figure 13",
  FontColor->GrayLevel[0]],
 ".) Change in ",
 StyleBox["f",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " due to increasing ",
 StyleBox["q",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " is almost imperceptible in comparison to reducing ",
 StyleBox["r",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 ", at least when ",
 StyleBox["r",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 " is small enough. "
}], "Text",
